DCEL Implementaon
The DCEL consists of three types of records:
1. Vertex records: Each vertex record stores the coordinates of a vertex and a list of
incident edges.
2. Edge records: Each edge record stores the two verces that the edge connects, a pointer
to the edge that is next in clockwise order around the rst vertex, a pointer to the edge
that is next in clockwise order around the second vertex, and pointers to the two faces
that are adjacent to the edge.
3. Face records: Each face record stores a pointer to one of the edges that bounds the face.
The DCEL data structure is ecient for a number of operaons on planar subdivisions, including
traversing the subdivision, nding the neighbours of a vertex or face, compung the intersecon
of two subdivisions, and many others.
For the given paper, we are trying to paron the given arbitrary polygon into convex parons
using DCEL. For implementaon of the algorithm we do not need the informaon of faces. To
implement verces we have created three structs – Vertex (storing x,y and leaving Halfedge),
Halfedge(storing origin vertex, twin Halfedge and next, previous Halfedge). A halfedge is
basically an edge that has been divided into 2 halfedges. To store the input verces of the
polygon, we have created a class DCEL, which has two main vectors – verces of type Vertex,
halfedges of type Halfedge. Class DCEL has two primary funcons – add_vertex and
add_halfedge to take input and store in DCEL.
Algorithm Explanaon
This algorithm is used to paron a given simple polygon with n verces into convex polygons.
The input to the algorithm is a set of verces of the polygon, provided in clockwise order, stored
in a cyclic list P. In our case we store the input points in the verces vector of class DCEL and we
push the index of each point in the vector P. We connue to work on index and access the data
points vis the verces vector whenever required.
The algorithm works by maintaining a set of verces in l that do not contain any notches –
where notch is a point that makes the polygon non convex. At each iteraon, it selects (v_i-1,
v_i+1), where v_i is the current vertex under consideraon (In the code we have taken v_i0, v_i
and v_i1 to store the indices of these verces), and checks if any of these points are a notch by
the isAcuteangle funcon dened above in the code. Only if these angles are all less than 180
that we move the verces forward and add a new vertex upcoming in p to the list l.
The algorithm connues this process unl there are only three verces remaining in P. At this
point, the polygon is already convex, and the algorithm terminates.
In case a notch is detected in the previous step, we then dene a list lpvs which is a set of
verces in p but not in l and also consists only and only of notches.
If aer the above operaons the size of LPVS is greater than 0 the algorithm proceeds to
remove the verces in LPVS that are outside the rectangle formed by the x_min, x_max, y_min,
y_max coordinates in L_m, and then checks if any vertex now le in LPVS lies inside the polygon
generated by L_m. If there is such a vertex, the algorithm obtains a set VTR of verces of L_m in
the semi plane generated by v1 and v(where v is the rst point of LPVS inside the polygon). We
now pop those verces from L_m that lie to the same side of the semi plane as that of L_last. As
soon as we nd a vertex in L_m that is on the opposite side of the semi plane we generate a
convex polygon with the current verces of L_m and update P and iteravely connue the
algorithm.
If no vertex in LPVS lies inside the polygon generated by L_m, the algorithm sets the ag
Backward to false. The algorithm then connues to the next vertex v_i+1.
If the last vertex in L_m is not equal to the vertex v_2, the algorithm writes L_m as a convex
polygon of the paron and removes the verces of L_m from P. The algorithm then proceeds
to the next convex polygon, starng with a new L_m.
The output of the algorithm is a set of convex polygons that paron the input polygon.
